President Donald Trump has announced his intent to nominate Eugene Scalia as the Secretary of Labor. Scalia is a renowned labor, employment, and regulatory lawyer, currently working as a partner at Gibson, Dunn & Crutcher LLP. He has previously held various positions in the Federal Government, including serving as a speechwriter to Secretary of Education William J. Bennett and as a Special Assistant to Attorney General William P. Barr. Scalia also served as the Solicitor of Labor at the Department of Labor in 2001, responsible for a broad range of regulatory and enforcement matters. He is a senior fellow of the Administrative Conference of the United States and has taught labor and employment law at the University of Chicago Law School and the University of the District of Columbia David A. Clarke School of Law. Scalia graduated cum laude from the University of Chicago Law School, where he served as editor-in-chief of the University of Chicago Law Review.